<ns2532:section xmlns:ns2532="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xml:id="resources.information.technologies.java.j2ee.ejb.introduction.javaBeansVsEjbs">

  <ns2533:title xmlns:ns2533="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Java Beans versus Enterprise Java Beans</ns2533:title>
  <ns2534:para xmlns:ns2534="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    Java Beans specifies a standard way for objects to publish their attributes and
    services as well as state change event sources and handlers. 
    This enables technologies like Visual
    Builders and EJB application servers to explore Java objects automatically.
    Java Beans thus facilitates a component based visual development process.
  </ns2534:para>
  <ns2535:para xmlns:ns2535="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    Enterprise Java Beans, on the other hand, are business logic components which
    are deployed in an application server. Business processes can be assembled from
    these business logic components.
  </ns2535:para>
  
  <ns2536:section xmlns:ns2536="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    <ns2537:title xmlns:ns2537="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Java Beans Technology and EJB Application Servers</ns2537:title>
    <ns2538:para xmlns:ns2538="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
      In the case of EJB applications servers, the application server discovers the
      services offered by the deployed enterprise bean and wraps it by an object which makes
      the bean network enabled and applies enterprise services like persistence, transactions
      and security to them.
    </ns2538:para>
  </ns2536:section>
</ns2532:section>